activity with impaired metabolism","Impaired electrical activity with preserved metabolic function","Complete tissue necrosis with no viable cells","Normal electrical and metabolic function with reduced blood flow"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe ischaemic penumbra is characterised by \u003Cstrong\u003Eimpaired electrical activity with preserved metabolic function\u003C/strong\u003E. This region surrounds the infarct core and represents potentially salvageable tissue if blood flow is restored quickly enough.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete loss of both electrical and metabolic activity\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes the infarct core, not the penumbra\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal electrical activity with impaired metabolism\u003C/strong\u003E - Electrical activity is always impaired before metabolic dysfunction\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComplete tissue necrosis with no viable cells\u003C/strong\u003E - This describes dead tissue, while penumbra is still viable\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ENormal electrical and metabolic function with reduced blood flow\u003C/strong\u003E - Electrical function is impaired in the penumbra due to reduced blood flow\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe presence of preserved metabolic activity in the penumbra makes this tissue potentially salvageable, providing an important target for acute stroke interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The ischaemic penumbra is potentially salvageable brain tissue surrounding an infarct core that has impaired electrical activity but preserved metabolic function.","The penumbra can be saved if blood flow is restored quickly, making it a key target for acute stroke interventions."],"references":["Ermine CM, Bivard A, Parsons MW, Baron JC. The ischemic penumbra: From concept to reality. Int J Stroke. 2021 Jul;16(5):497-509. doi: 10.1177/1747493020975229. Epub 2020 Dec 1. PMID: 33818215.","Liu S, Levine SR, Winn HR. Targeting ischemic penumbra: part I - from pathophysiology to therapeutic strategy. J Exp Stroke Transl Med. 2010 Mar 15;3(1):47-55. doi: 10.6030/1939-067x-3.1.47. PMID: 20607107; PMCID: PMC2896002.","Yang SH, Liu R. Four Decades of Ischemic Penumbra and Its Implication for Ischemic Stroke. Transl Stroke Res. 2021 Dec;12(6):937-945. doi: 10.1007/s12975-021-00916-2. Epub 2021 Jul 5. PMID: 34224106; PMCID: PMC8557134."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61207"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16467"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"61207","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/61207"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-30T15:46:55+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-01T13:04:58+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9158"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"75689"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","nam